\f1\fs32 The units of time in use throughout the world are: \
\pard\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Second
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (s): The second is the base unit of time in the SI system. It was historically defined as 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\fs32 1\uc0\u8260 86400
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  of a day \'96 this factor derived from the division of the day first into 24 hours, then to 60 minutes per hour and finally to 60 seconds per minute (24 \'d7 60 \'d7 60 = 86400 seconds per day). This definition is not sufficiently accurate for many purposes because of irregularities in the earth's orbit around the sun, so the second is now formally defined as the duration of 9,192,631,770 cycles of the radiation produced by the cesium-133 atom. \
For time intervals smaller than a second,  SI prefixes are used.  One millisecond is 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\fs32 10^\{-3\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  seconds; 1 microsecond is 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\fs32 10^\{-6\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  seconds; 1 nanosecond is 
\f0\fs24 \cf3 <$Scr_Cs::3>
\f3\fs32 10^\{-9\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  seconds; and 1 picosecond is 
