\f3\fs32 10^\{-12\}
\f0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::3>
\f1\fs32  seconds.\

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Minute
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (min): One minute is equal to 60 seconds. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Hour
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (h): One hour is equal to 60 minutes or 3,600 seconds. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Day
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (d): One day is defined as 24 hours, or 86,400 seconds. It is based on the Earth's rotation period. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Week:
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  A week consists of seven days. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Month
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32 : Months are somewhat arbitrary units of time that vary in length. The most common definitions are the calendar months, which have 28, 30, or 31 days. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Year
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32  (yr): A year is the time it takes for Earth to complete one orbit around the Sun. It is approximately 365.25 days. 
\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Decade
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32 : A decade is a period of ten years. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Century
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32 : A century is a period of one hundred years. \

\f0\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f2\b\fs32 Millennium
\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f1\fs32 : A millennium is a period of one thousand years. \
These units provide a way to express and measure various durations, from tiny fractions of a second to vast spans of time. \
